height, and mapping height over a strictly monotone function or order-isomorphism

From the Carleson project

Review comment: This helper lemma is used more often in https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/15524, hence extracted.

Horror! Don't use topology for such simple statement :-)

See how [`ENNReal.iSup_add`](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Topology/Instances/ENNReal.html#ENNReal.iSup_add) is proved and try doing the same for `ENat`

That looks very similar to me:
```
theorem iSup_add {ι : Sort*} {s : ι → ℝ≥0∞} [Nonempty ι] : iSup s + a = ⨆ b, s b + a :=
  Monotone.map_ciSup_of_continuousAt (continuousAt_id.add continuousAt_const) <|
    monotone_id.add monotone_const
```

I have a non-topological ugly proof in https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/15344/files, but [was advised](https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/287929-mathlib4/topic/Topology.20of.20.60ENat.60/near/455447883) to use https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/15380. Was that ill-advised?
Oh, that looks quite bad. Certainly, the elementary theory of heights should not require topology. I will try to open a PR downgrading the imports to `ENNReal.iSup_add`.
Sorry for the delay, I am attending a summer school this week but I am still working on this. Expect the PR tonight or tomorrow.
Thanks for the heads up, and no rush!
The PRs are #16735 and #16742. Do you want me to prove the `ENat` versions as well or are you happy to take it from there?

I can give it a shot when I get to it, but not sure when that will be, and will probably require some hand holding. So if you have pages it all in and have a clear picture where to go, maybe better go ahead?
Okay, will do it myself

```suggestion
@[gcongr] lemma height_strictMono {x y : α} (hxy : x < y) (hfin : height y < ⊤) :
```

```suggestion
lemma height_le_height_apply_of_strictMono {f : α → β} (hf : StrictMono f) (x : α) :
```

```suggestion
lemma height_orderIso (f : α ≃o β) (x : α) : height (f x) = height x := by
```
or something like that
I thought we said no `iSup` API anymore 😉
Well, after `height_add_const` there is an `iSup` again. So at least the first one is hard to avoid. The other one I can do differently.

```suggestion
    height a + n = ⨆ (p : LTSeries α) (_ : p.last = a), p.length + n := by
```

```suggestion
@[gcongr] lemma height_strictMono {x y : α} (hxy : x < y) (hfin : height x < ⊤) :
```
because if `y` has infinite height then its height is greater than `height x`

I think I thought multiple times which one is the more general statement, but seems I got it wrong nevertheless :-). Thanks!

(Will fix the proof later)

```suggestion
    have hnetop : height x ≠ ⊤ := ne_top_of_lt hfin
```

```suggestion
  rw [← ENat.add_one_le_iff hfin.ne, height_add_const, iSup₂_le_iff]
```

```suggestion
lemma height_le_height_apply_of_strictMono (f : α → β) (hf : StrictMono f) (x : α) :
```
